              <p class="text-[#D4D4D4]">The historic Gallatin Square features attached brick buildings where restaurants share walls with retail shops, offices, and residential units. A grease fire in one kitchen duct can spread through an entire block of connected structures. But many of these kitchens operate with older, non-standard ductwork hidden behind drop ceilings and plaster walls — ductwork that lacks the fire-rated access panels required for a full NFPA 96 bare-metal cleaning. The Gallatin Fire Prevention Division treats the downtown overlay as a zero-tolerance enforcement zone, and DDAN regularly installs the specialized access panels needed to bring these historic systems into compliance without damaging the building's character.</p>
